title: Architecture

ORY Hive supports two authentication flows:

- Browser-based (easy): This flow works for all applications running on top of a browser. Websites, single-page apps, Cordova/Ionic,
and so on.
- API-based (advanced): This flow works for native applications like iOS, android, .NET.

ORY Hive can act as an OAuth 2.0 Authorization Server or an OpenID Connect Provider in combination with ORY Hydra. This
is for advanced usecases where third party applications need access to first-party user data.

## Browser-based

The browser-based authentication flow relies on cookies for proof of authentication. The browser-based flow is suitable
for usecases where the application is running in the browser. This is the case for regular websites / webapps, single-page
applications, and webview-based applications like Ionic or Cordova.

Benefits:
- The browser-based flow can be set up within seconds using Ory Cloud. Adding additional authentication mechanisms like
Social Sign-In, SAML, Kerberos works with a few clicks or API calls.
- The browser-based flow does not require any type of access or refresh token complexity. It is the most secure
mechanism for browser applications and does not require storage of sensitive credentials in the XSS-vulnerable localstorage.

Caveats:
- The browser-based flow does not work across top-level domains (e.g. mydomain.com and myotherdomain.com).
- This flow does not work in the context of pure mobile native applications because a browser is required.

### Credential-based Authentication Flow

The password credentials authentication flow is the most basic authentication mechanism. It uses a combination of
a unique user identifier (username, email, phone number) and a password.

#### API

Login Page UI:

```
GET /authn/request

Location: https://login-ui/?challenge=...
```

Methods:

```
{
	"name": "password"
	"type": "form",
	"action":  "https://url/challenge",
	"fields": [
		{
			"name": "identity",
			"type": "text"
		},
		{
			"name": "csrf_token",
			"type": "hidden",
			"value": "....",
			"required": true
		},
		{
			"name": "password",
			"type": "password",
			"required": true
		}
	]
}
```

## Server-Side Authentication Flow

```
sequenceDiagram

participant U as Browser
participant LP as Server-Side Login Page
participant HRP as Hive Reverse Proxy
participant HA as Hive Admin API
participant HP as Hive Public API
participant SP as Protected Endpoint or Page

U->>HRP: Request Page
HRP-->>HRP: Not authenticated
HRP-->HA: Initiate Auth Session
HRP->>U: Redirect to Login Page
U->>LP: Open Login Page
LP-->HP: Init session, fetch auth methods
LP-->>LP: Render HTML with auth methods, csrf, ...
LP->>U: Respond with HTML
U->>LP: Pick auth method, send creds
LP-->HP: Validate creds, receive session init url
LP->>U: Forward to session init url
U->>HRP: Call session init url
HRP-->>HRP: Set up session
HRP->>U: Forward to previous url or post-login url
U-->>U: Do stuff, e.g. open web page
U->>HRP: Request protected page, send cookie
HRP-->>HRP: Validate session cookie
HRP-->SP: Forward request
HRP->>U: Respond with payload
```

## Client-side Authentication Flow (Browser)

```
sequenceDiagram

participant U as Browser
participant SPA as Browser App (React, ..)
participant LP as SPA Login Page
participant HRP as Hive Reverse Proxy
participant HA as Hive Admin API
participant HP as Hive Public API
participant SP as Protected Endpoint or Page

U->>SPA: Request Page
SPA->>HRP: Is authenticated?
HRP-->>HRP: Not authenticated
HRP-->HA: Initiate Auth Session
HRP->>SPA: Not authenticated, send login URL
SPA->>U: Redirect to Login URL
U->>LP: Open Login Page
LP-->HP: Init session, fetch auth methods
LP-->>LP: Render HTML with auth methods, csrf, ...
LP->>U: Respond with HTML
U->>LP: Pick auth method, send creds
LP-->HP: Validate creds, receive session init url
LP->>U: Forward to session init url
U->>HRP: Call session init url
HRP-->>HRP: Set up session
HRP->>U: Forward to previous url or post-login url
U-->>U: Do stuff, e.g. open web page
U->>SPA: Request protected page, send cookie
SPA->>HRP: Make API request
HRP-->>HRP: Validate session cookie
HRP-->SP: Forward request
HRP->>U: Respond with payload
```




## Login UI


Applications running and rendering on the server-side, such as a PHP application which renders an HTML page, initiate
an authentication session with the Hive API and render the resulting information as they see fit.

To initiate the session, the server-side code handling the login page makes a request to the Hive API
`POST https://hive.something/authentication/session` and receives the available authentication methods:

```
{
    "id": "abcde",
    "csrf_token": "bcde",
    "methods": [
        {
            "type": "passwordless",
        },
        {
            "type": "password",
            "options": {
                "email_url": "https://hive.something/authentication/session/password/email",
                "phone_url": "https://hive.something/authentication/session/password/phone",
                "username_url": "https://hive.something/authentication/session/password/username",
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "oidc",
            "options": {
                "provider": "google",
                "url": "https://google.com/..."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "oidc",
            "options": {
                "provider": "github",
                "url": "https://github.com/..."
            }
        },
    ]
}
```
